  <static seed="71" source="Contrib/PCC/BasicAlgebra/FractionArithmetic/AddFractions90.pg">
    <statement><p>Add: <m>\displaystyle{ 4 + \frac{2}{5}}</m></p>
<p><fillin characters="11" name="AnSwEr0001"/></p>
</statement>
    <answer>
      <p>
        <m>{\frac{22}{5}}</m>
      </p>
    </answer>
    <solution><p>When doing arithmetic with fractions, it is helpful to rewrite any integers as fractions:</p>
<p><m>\displaystyle{ 4 = \frac{4}{1} }</m></p>
<p>Next, to add two fractions, we need to find a common denominator. In this case, it is simply the second denominator <m>5</m>. We will rewrite the first fraction:</p>
<p><m>\displaystyle{ \begin{aligned}\frac{4}{1} \amp = \frac{4 \cdot 5}{1 \cdot 5}\\ \amp = \frac{20}{5} \end{aligned}}</m></p>
<p>Finally, we add the numerators and keep the denominator unchanged. The whole process is:</p>
<p><m>\displaystyle{\begin{aligned}
   4 + \frac{2}{5}
        \amp = \frac{20}{5} + \frac{2}{5} \\
        \amp = \frac{20 + 2}{5} \\
        \amp = \frac{22}{5}
\end{aligned}
    }</m></p>
<p>The answer to this question is  <m>{{\frac{22}{5}}}</m>.</p>
</solution>
